\par\plain 
\par\plain {\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  kill the whole family, but say you only killed two. It will keep the numbers down.}
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 I myself remember an \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93examining justice\u8221\'94 telling one of my comrades (a man who had been arrested for \u8220\'93counter-revolution\u8221\'94 during the February of 1920) that, \u8220\'93although we cannot shoot you here, we\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 can}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~send you to the front for the purpose.\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 And that \u8220\'93front\u8221\'94 (it needs hardly to be added) was by no means limited to the regions where civil war was in actual progress.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 In 1921 the Bolshevists took 600 persons from different prisons of Petrograd, dispatched them to Kronstadt, loaded}{\f0\fs24\b0 [}{\f0\fs24\b0 69]\~them on to a barge, and scuttled the vessel at a particularly deep spot. All but one were drowned. And he only escaped because he was able to swim to the Finnish shore.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/77104/pg77104-images.html#Footnote_70"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\cf4 70]}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 As soon as ever, in 1920, the Bolshevists had made their third entry into Odessa, daily executions of 100 or more persons became the rule, and motor-lorries had to cart away the dead in heaps}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 Merciless, shameless looting is going on, with the Bolshevists robbing the shops and houses of the\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 bourgeoisie}{\f0\fs24\b0 , but, still more, the co-operative stores. And they keep shooting officers, or else hacking them to pieces with swords\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 sometimes in the street as soon as caught, and sometimes in the officers\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92 homes.... Recently, too, they set fire to the military hospital on the corner of the Taganrog Prospekt and Temeritskaya Street, although the building was crowded with sick and wounded officers at the time, and many of the latter were too weak to move. In fact, forty were burnt to death.... The exact number of shot and hacked is not yet known. All that is known is that the number must have been very large. And with each addition to the local soviet\u8217\'92s power its methods are growing bolder. First it placed the whole of the Cossack population under surveillance. Then it brought into operation a Che-Ka under Peters, and kept the engines of two motor lorries in constant running, that the sound of the shots might not be heard outside the building.... Peters frequently attends the executions in person. They take place in batches, with perhaps as many as ninety persons shot in a single night.}
